a women’s affair, preferring the wives to be solely responsible for handling the difficulties surrounding divorce. According to the recently released State of the Mozambican Family report, some men believe that divorce belongs to only the woman and not them, even if they initiated the separation. They rather think that it is a matter of the woman going to a lawyer and reaching an agreement. This attitude is not shared at all by women.

To read the report, please visit: http://www.isdstheri.org/4th_moc_dissemination_english.pdf

For insights into family law and policy in Mozambique, please read: http://www.fic.ntrm.mz/UploadedFile/FamilyLawPR_EN.pdf

For more information on causalities and obstacles that prevent women from accessing the legal system, read this June 2017 report on Gender Gap in Mozambique: http://www.divorcelaw.africa/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/A-Gendergap-analysis-in-Mozambique-2017-1.pdf

To read more about problems women face accessing justice in Uganda, please read this: http://www.divorcelaw.africa/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/OBJECTIONS_BY_Uganda_in_relation_to_CCPR.docx

By Heff Mugambi

A WED office assistant cum international qualitative researcher based in Kenya was hungry, exhausted and did a lot of walking. All she needed to do was work in the legal sector
